<DOC><DOCNO> AP880601-0262 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2208EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Slaying     06-01 0236</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-Slaying,0243</SECOND><HEAD>Film Set Designer Slain</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   British film-set designer Tessa Davies, who workedon the movie ``The Killing Fields,'' was found dead in a pool ofblood and her companion unconscious in their home near London,police said Wednesday night.   Richard Furgerson, a TV set designer who owns the house, wasreported hospitalized in serious condition.   Detective Superintendent John Childerley said there was no signof a struggle. He said the 47-year-old Miss Davies, found in adownstairs room, was killed by heavy blows to her head with somehousehold object. Childerley said Furgerson, 51, was in a bedroomupstairs.   Police said they were not looking for a third party.   Furgerson's ex-wife lives near the house and they have two sonsin their late 20s, Childerley said.   Police said they broke into the house at Hurley near Maidenhead,soon after dawn, after receiving an emergency telephone call from afriend in London who was worried about the couple.   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, said MissDavies dressed the sets for David Puttnam's ``The Killing Fields''in 1984, about the communist takeover of Cambodia, and wasnominated for an Academy Award. It said she was also nominated foran Academy Award for her work with Barbra Streisand in ``Yentl.''   Her latest film, which she had just completed on location inMexico, was ``The Old Gringo,'' starring Jane Fonda, the agencyreported.</TEXT></DOC>